- cs.IT (Information Theory) is the most likely category as the paper deals with optimal prefix-free codes and Huffman coding, which are fundamental concepts in information theory.
- cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms) is also likely as the paper proposes an algorithm for constructing optimal skeleton Huffman trees.
- cs.SI (Social and Information Networks) is less likely but still possible as Huffman coding is commonly used in network communication and data compression.
- cs.DC (Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing) is less likely but still possible as the paper mentions the potential for faster decoding and speeding up wavelet trees.
- cs.LG (Machine Learning) is the least likely category as the paper does not explicitly mention any machine learning applications or techniques.
